{"title_page": "Charles L. Kane", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Charles L. Kane\n| image = Charles L. Kane.jpg\n| image_size = 250\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1963|1|12}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = \n| residence = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]\n| citizenship = [[United States of America]]\n| nationality = [[Americans|American]]\n| fields = [[Theoretical physics|Theoretical]] [[condensed matter physics]]\n| workplaces = [[University of Pennsylvania]]\n| alma_mater = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], [[University of Chicago]]\n| doctoral_advisor = \n| academic_advisors = [[Patrick A. Lee]]\n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| awards = [[Dirac Prize]] {{small|(2012)}}<br />[[Oliver E. Buckley Condensed Matter Prize|Oliver E. Buckley Prize]] {{small|(2012)}}<br />[[Breakthrough Prize in Fundamental Physics|Physics Frontiers Prize]] {{small|(2013)}}<br />[[Benjamin Franklin Medal (Franklin Institute)|Franklin Medal]] {{small|(2015)}}<br />[[BBVA Foundation Frontiers of Knowledge Award|Fontiers of Knowledge Award]] {{small|(2018)}}<br>[[Breakthrough Prize in Fundamental Physics]] {{small|(2019)}}\n| signature = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt = \n| footnotes = \n| spouse = [[Suzanne Amador Kane]]\n| website = \n}}'''Charles L. Kane''' (born January 12, 1963) is a [[theoretical physics|theoretical]] [[condensed matter physics|condensed matter physicist]] and is the Christopher H. Browne Distinguished Professor of Physics at the [[University of Pennsylvania]].  He completed a B.S. in physics at the [[University of Chicago]] in 1985 and his Ph.D. at [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] in 1989. Prior to joining the faculty at the University of Pennsylvania he was a postdoctoral associate at [[IBM]]'s [[T. J. Watson Research Center]] working with his mentor [[Matthew P. A. Fisher]], among others.\n\nKane is notable for theoretically predicting the [[quantum spin Hall effect]] (originally in graphene) and what would later be known as [[topological insulator]]s.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brumfiel|first=Geoff|date=2010-07-01|title=Topological insulators: Star material|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/466310a|journal=Nature News|language=en|volume=466|issue=7304|pages=310\u2013311|doi=10.1038/466310a|issn=1476-4687|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hasan|first=M. Zahid|last2=Kane|first2=Charles L.|date=2010-11-08|title=Topological Insulators|url=https://link.aps.org/doi/10.1103/RevModPhys.82.3045|journal=Reviews of Modern Physics|language=en|volume=82|issue=4|pages=3045\u20133067|doi=10.1103/RevModPhys.82.3045|issn=0034-6861|via=}}</ref>\n\nHe received the 2012 [[Dirac Prize]], along with [[Shoucheng Zhang]] and [[Duncan Haldane]], for their groundbreaking work on two- and three-dimensional [[topological insulators]].<ref>[http://www.ictp.it/about-ictp/prizes-awards/the-dirac-medal/the-medallists-%281%29/dirac-medallists-2012.aspx Dirac prize citation - 2012]</ref><ref>{{Cite web\n| last = Durrani, Matin\n| title = Condensed-matter trio scoop Dirac prize - physicsworld.com\n| accessdate = 2013-02-06\n| url = http://physicsworld.com/cws/article/news/2012/aug/08/condensed-matter-trio-scoop-dirac-prize\n| date = 2012-08-08\n}}</ref>  In the same year he was also chosen for the inaugural class of Mathematics and the Physical Sciences [[Simons Investigator]]s.<ref>[https://simonsfoundation.org/program-areas/mathematics-and-physical-science/simons-investigators/ Simons Investigators]</ref><ref>[http://www.upenn.edu/pennnews/news/penn-s-charles-kane-named-simons-investigator-and-awarded-500000-grant Penn\u2019s Charles Kane Named Simons Investigator and Awarded $500,000 Grant]</ref>  He also shared one of the 2013 [[Physics Frontiers prize]]s with [[Laurens Molenkamp]] and [[Shoucheng Zhang]] for their work on topological insulators.<ref>{{Cite web\n| last = Hamish Johnston\n| title = Higgs hunters and Stephen Hawking bag new $3m prizes - physicsworld.com\n| accessdate = 2013-02-06\n| url = http://physicsworld.com/cws/article/news/2012/dec/11/higgs-hunters-and-stephen-hawking-bag-new-3m-prizes\n| date = 2012-12-11\n}}</ref> \nIn 2018 he shared the [[BBVA Foundation Frontiers of Knowledge Award|Fontiers of Knowledge Award]] with [[Eugene Mele]]. In 2019 was recognized with [[Breakthrough Prize in Fundamental Physics]] with fellow University of Pennsylvania professor Eugene Mele, again for work on topological insulators.<ref>{{Cite web\n| last = Baillie, Katherine Unger \n| title = Eugene Mele and Charles Kane to share Breakthrough Prize in Fundamental Physics\n| accessdate = 2018-10-17\n| url = https://penntoday.upenn.edu/news/charles-kane-and-eugene-mele-share-breakthrough-prize-fundamental-physics\n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Breakthrough Prize laureates|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kane, Charles L.}}\n[[Category:21st-century American physicists]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Physical Society]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Simons Investigator]]\n[[Category:MIT Department of Physics alumni]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Charles L. Kane\n| image = Charles L. Kane.jpg\n| image_size = 250\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1963|1|12}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = \n| residence = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]\n| citizenship = [[United States of America]]\n| nationality = [[Americans|American]]\n| fields = [[Theoretical physics|Theoretical]] [[condensed matter physics]]\n| workplaces = [[University of Pennsylvania]]\n| alma_mater = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], [[University of Chicago]]\n| doctoral_advisor = \n| academic_advisors = [[Patrick A. Lee]]\n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| awards = [[Dirac Prize]] {{small|(2012)}}<br />[[Oliver E. Buckley Condensed Matter Prize|Oliver E. Buckley Prize]] {{small|(2012)}}<br />[[Breakthrough Prize in Fundamental Physics|Physics Frontiers Prize]] {{small|(2013)}}<br />[[Benjamin Franklin Medal (Franklin Institute)|Franklin Medal]] {{small|(2015)}}<br />[[BBVA Foundation Frontiers of Knowledge Award|Fontiers of Knowledge Award]] {{small|(2018)}}<br>[[Breakthrough Prize in Fundamental Physics]] {{small|(2019)}}\n| signature = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt = \n| footnotes = \n| spouse = [[Suzanne Amador Kane]]\n| website = \n}}'''Charles L. Kane''' (born January 12, 1963) is a [[theoretical physics|theoretical]] [[condensed matter physics|condensed matter physicist]] and is the Christopher H. Browne Distinguished Professor of Physics at the [[University of Pennsylvania]].  He completed a B.S. in physics at the [[University of Chicago]] in 1985 and his Ph.D. at [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] in 1989. Prior to joining the faculty at the University of Pennsylvania he was a postdoctoral associate at [[IBM]]'s [[T. J. Watson Research Center]] working with his mentor [[Matthew P. A. Fisher]], among others.\n\nKane is notable for theoretically predicting the [[quantum spin Hall effect]] (originally in graphene) and what would later be known as [[topological insulator]]s.<ref>{{Cite journal\n| doi = 10.1038/466310a\n| issn = 0028-0836\n| volume = 466\n| issue = 7304\n| pages = 310\u2013311\n| last = Brumfiel\n| first = Geoff\n| title = Topological insulators: Star material\n| journal = Nature News\n| accessdate = 2013-02-06\n| date